As an ex-model who used to hate holidays because she didn’t want to gain weight… I know how holidays can be extremely stressful for some people.

The thing is, two to four days out of the year of eating a little extra is not going to ruin your overall progress.

Being stressed and not enjoying yourself will ruin your progress more than just enjoying the cookie and moving on.

Instead of stressing about what you can’t eat, try adding in things to help your body utilize the extra carbs and calories.

💪🏻 The best thing you can do is activate your muscles in the morning by doing a 20 to 30 minute strength training workout or by taking a nice walk after any big meals.

This will help you to use the glucose coming in to build muscle instead of storing it as fat or causing inflammation!

Enjoy the holidays, that’s what they’re there for!

We always hear this from everyone every year around this time…

“I’ll start Monday. I’ll start in the New Year. I’ll start after this event!”

The thing is, that is setting you up for you trying to do everything perfectly for a few weeks and then quitting as soon as you fall of track. 

What if you just started with simple habits that you can do today, tomorrow, for weeks and for months.

Starting everyday with a high protein breakfast sets your metabolism up for stable energy, continuous fat burn and less sugar cravings.

Hydrating with electrolytes ensures that your cells are actually getting the water they need into the cell instead of just drinking water and it getting absorbed poorly 

Activating your muscles, even if it’s just a 10-20 minute walk helps to use stored glucose and reduce inflammation.

What if you just did these three things today and stopped forcing yourself to be a “perfect” person in the New Year?

Comment a ❤️ below if this helped you!

As the new year rolls around I want to take a second to reintroduce myself and share my story on this platform to the people who have been here since the beginning and the new people who might not know me at all!

Hi, my name is Tess Richardson and for about 10 years I was a high fashion model in New York, Los Angeles, Mexico, Germany and other places around the world.

As much as modeling brought me amazing experiences that I will never forget, it was extremely hard for me mentally and physically. 

I was continuously being told to lose weight, even with my naturally tall frame and my measurements were just never quite good enough. I lived so many years stressed about 1-2 little inches around my hips and being told that I was “too fat” 🙄 that I fell into very dark places. 

Something amazing did happen during those times though…

I became obsessed with how I can “biohack” my body to be the skinniest I could be. Now this is not what I should have been using my research for, but I began to fall in love with this world of science and Biohacking. 

So much that I quit modeling and moved to LA to work at the Mecca of Biohacking at that time, Bulletproof Upgrade Labs. There, I trained some of the top people in the health space on the newest technologies, and I LOVED it.

After it shut down during the pandemic I decided I wanted to take that same technology that I had discovered there and help people to understand how to utilize it to optimize their health too. 

That’s when I started Hacked Healthy and began working with amazing clients around the world, teaching them how to understand their data and the hacks to improve it. 

This year has been a whirlwind for my business and I couldn’t be more grateful for my incredible clients, the opportunities I have become a part of and all the doors that seemed to swing open due to my love and passion for what I do.

If you are someone who wants to stop trying random diets to lose weight and become healthier and start really understanding how your unique metabolism and body works, send me a quick DM and we can set up a free consultation to start the new year! 

Thanks for reading this far 🤍

Metabolic flexibility is the ability to switch back and forth between using glucose or sugar for fuel and using fat for fuel easily. 

When you are not metabolically flexible, you can’t go for more than four hours without food, you get “hangry” and it is hard to extend a fast past 10-12 hours. 

Being metabolically FLEXIBLE means that you are able to eat carbs but also be able to switch back into a stable fat burning mood very efficiently.

To become metabolically flexible we have to learn how to utilize the glucose we are taking in and how to access our fat cells more efficiently through diet and lifestyle hacks and habits!

My biggest question from my client, “What can I do on vacation to make sure I don’t lose progress?”

I always tell them a few hacks but in reality, especially if it’s a shorter vacation I tell them to fully enjoy and just do the things they can without pressure! 

Here are 5 simple things you can do to stay balanced on your next trip:

1. Movement when you can - if you have a gym then continuing with at least 50% of your workouts but if not then just doing body weight or band exercises to keep your muscles active throughout the day

2. Cold Showers - Taking a 1-2 minute cold shower in the morning can help to reduce inflammation daily and help you to continue in a fat burning mode (if that is your goal) and feel better so you can enjoy more! 

3. Get sunlight in the morning and sleep at night when possible. When we give up sleep that is when we really get into trouble, so if you do nothing else, take care of your circadian rythyms and get some deep rest so your body can restore.

4. When you can, find nature - grounding and resetting our bodies natural frequencies is a sure fire way to make sure we are actually restoring during our vacation and not going to need a “vacation from my vacation” when you get back. It also can help with sleep and energy!

5. Don’t sit after meals - This is one of the bigger ones I tell clients. when we said, after meals, we don’t utilize the Glucose or Energy, that we just took in. When reactivate my muscles were able to use the energy to feed our muscles instead of our fat cells. Taking a 10 to 15 minute walk after your meals is one of the best tax you can do for keeping your glucose balanced 🦾

What are your favorite travel hacks? Put them in the comments below! ⬇️

When it comes to stress, there is the good and then there is the bad 😵‍💫

Good stressors are things like exercise, sauna, fasting, cold therapy etc. with good balance these stressors make your body stronger over time.

Then we have chronic stressors like work stress, money stress, toxic environment, inflammatory foods, emotional stress. 

Chronic stress is what leads to slower metabolism, immune issues and overall lower quality of health. 

Here are 3 signs chronic stress is impacting your metabolic health: 

1️⃣ Persistent Fatigue: Feeling constantly drained? It’s more than exhaustion – chronic stress might be dimming your metabolic fire, leaving you fatigued and worn out

2️⃣ Craving Complexity: Complex carbs and sugary cravings surging? These yearnings could be stress-induced, as your metabolism struggles under the weight of tension.

3️⃣ Weighted Struggle: Unexplained weight shifts? Stress triggers hormonal upheavals, potentially sabotaging your metabolism’s equilibrium and leading to unexpected changes.

Empower yourself with awareness. Managing stress isn’t just for peace of mind; it’s crucial for safeguarding your body’s intricate balance. 

If your body is giving you these signs then it is time to slow down and rest 🌱

 #MetabolismInsights #StressAwareness”

Chronic stress is one of the biggest threats to our metabolic health, and almost all of us deal with it on a daily basis! 🔥

Did you know chronic stress:
- Turns off or slows down digestion
- Turns off fertility hormones
- Increases blood glucose 

Just those will impact your metabolic health and quality of life…

So what can you do? 🤷🏻‍♀️

1. Find a hobby that is in nature, whether it is biking, hiking, walking your dog, rock climbing, swimming, etc. whatever pulls you out of the overstimulation and into the grounding of nature, will help you to reduce your stress

2. While you are in nature, ground yourself. When we go rock climbing, I am shoes off almost the whole time (unless I’m climbing) getting your feet in the dirt will recalibrate you faster than anything else 🌱

3. Taking breaks throughout your day to go outside into the sun. Just like being in nature can recalibrate you, just putting your face in the sun can be incredible for reducing cortisol and boosting your feel hood hormones. Take 20 minutes out of your day to get into the sun.

Obviously, the best way to reduce stress is to take out the stressors, but that is extremely hard in our modern society so the second best thing that you can do is learn how to recalibrate yourself continuously and come back into balance whenever you can 🧗‍♀️

My favorite right now is rock climbing if you haven’t noticed ☺️

INSULIN RESISTANCE 📈

Insulin resistance is when cells in your muscles, fat, and liver start resisting the hormone insulin’s signal—to help them absorb glucose from the bloodstream. This can lead to elevated blood sugar levels, setting the stage for prediabetes or type 2 diabetes.

The good news? You can take control NOW to begin reversing it. ⚡️

The best 3 ways to become more insulin sensitive:

1️⃣ Stabilizing glucose Levels: Glucose is what causes insulin to increase so stabilizing your levels can help you to reduce Insulin in the body
2️⃣ Prioritize protein: Protein helps to keep glucose levels low, increase muscle mass and improve metabolism
3️⃣ Activate your Metabolic Muscles: your muscles utilize 80% of the glucose you take in and do not need insulin to lower glucose levels.

The HACKS to use to mitigate stress when traveling ✈️

Flying can be extremely stressful on your body, with dehydration, over pollution of EMFS, dry air and jet lag. 

My favorite things to do to support my body when traveling:

1. Minerals in water @drinklmnt - about 1 bottle of water for every hour and one packet of LMNT or other mineral electrolyte at least per flight

2. Fasting: Especially on morning flights it is a great way to decrease both jet lag and reduce stress on digestion 

3. Put on my red light glasses on before and on night flights: the lights from the planes can disrupt natural circadian rhythms, so if you can wearing red light glasses can help you to sleep once you arrive 

4. Ground before and after the flight: EMF pollution is a huge factor of stress on our bodies when traveling. Wearing grounding shoes before or grounding in the earth for 10/15 minute before leaving for your flight and when you arrive can help to rebalance your cells and mitigate inflammation

Save this for your next flight ☺️

#biohacking #metabolichealth #staysalty #lmnt #electrolytes #hydration #travelhacks

Cravings are not about willpower 🧠

They're deeply rooted in our body's physiology and can be managed through strategic changes ✍️

1️⃣ Amino Acids from Protein: Consuming 25-30g of high-quality protein ensures a steady intake of essential amino acids. These building blocks are crucial for neurotransmitter production, which directly affects our mood and appetite. An imbalance can lead to cravings, especially for sugary or high-carb foods. Adequate protein intake also stabilizes blood sugar, further reducing those unwanted cravings.

2️⃣ Hydration with Minerals: You might think you're hungry when in reality, you're just thirsty. Proper hydration is vital for all our cellular functions. Adding quality salts or minerals to your water helps maintain electrolyte balance, which, when off-kilter, can manifest as cravings. Balanced electrolytes also support nerve function and muscle contractions, ensuring your body operates efficiently.

3️⃣ Healthy Fats: Fats play a pivotal role in hormone production, including those responsible for hunger and satiety. Consuming sources like avocado, olive oil, or ghee provides a slow, steady source of energy, keeping you full for longer. Moreover, fats help in the absorption of fat-soluble vitamins (A, D, E, K), optimizing overall health.

So, next time those cravings kick in, remember it's not a test of willpower but an opportunity to nourish your body right. Knowledge is power, and understanding the 'why' behind these steps is your secret weapon to conquering cravings. 💪

Let's dive into the science of cortisol and its sneaky role in belly fat accumulation ⬇

Cortisol, our body's stress hormone, isn't just about handling stress—it's a key player in our metabolic puzzle. 

When stress levels rise, cortisol kicks in and in our modern world, where stress is often constant, this system can overfire. ⚠️

Here's the twist: Elevated cortisol doesn't just float around harmlessly. It specifically influences fat storage, directing it straight to our abdomen. This isn't ordinary fat; it's visceral fat that wraps around vital organs. 

Unlike subcutaneous fat, visceral fat is metabolically active, affecting insulin sensitivity and increasing the risk for metabolic disorders. 🚨

The irony? The more stressed we are, the more cortisol we produce, and the more we predispose ourselves to central obesity. This isn't about overeating but how our body, under stress, manages energy and fat. 🔄

So, while we can't always eliminate stress, understanding cortisol's role can empower us to manage its impact. 

Here are three supplements you can use to start reducing chronic stress:

GABA (Gamma-Aminobutyric Acid): This neurotransmitter helps calm the nervous system

L-Theanine: Found primarily in green tea, this amino acid promotes relaxation without drowsiness

Magnesium: An essential mineral for over 300 biochemical reactions in the body, 

Let's respect our body's complex biology and work with it, not against it. Here's to a balanced life and a healthier you! 🌟
